<!DOCTYPE showme.pack
  SYSTEM "../Symbols.dtd">
<showme.pack xmlns="Compositor"
             xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
             id="Exa_BasisColumnSpace"
             xsi:schemaLocation="Compositor file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Compositor.xsd">
	  <texsupport xmlns="" href="../LinearAlgebraTeXSupport.xml"/>
	
	  <title>A Basis for the Column Space: Examples</title>
	
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para xmlns="">
            <para.body>Find a basis for the column space of the matrix</para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.display xmlns="">
				        <latex>
					
\Mtrx{A}\ =\ \left[
\begin{array}{rrrr}
1 &amp; 3 &amp; 2 &amp; -1 \\
1 &amp; 4 &amp; 3 &amp; -4 \\
1 &amp; 2 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 \\
1 &amp; 5 &amp; 4 &amp; -7
\end{array}\right]

				</latex>
			      </math.display>
		    </statement.showme>
		
		    <answer.showme xmlns="">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>The first step is to find the RREF of  <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math>:</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>
					
\begin{array}{cc}
\text{matrix $A$}\quad &amp;\quad \text{row reduced matrix $B$} \\
\begin{array}{rrrr}
1 &amp; 3 &amp; 2 &amp; -1 \\
1 &amp; 4 &amp; 3 &amp; -4 \\
1 &amp; 2 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 \\
1 &amp; 5 &amp; 4 &amp; -7
\end{array} &amp;
\begin{array}{rrrr}
1 &amp; 0 &amp; -1 &amp; 8 \\
0 &amp; 1 &amp; 1 &amp; -3 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0
\end{array}
\end{array}

				</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>The row reduced matrix <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                     </math> has two leading <math>
                        <latex>1</latex>
                     </math>'s, and these leading <math>
                        <latex>1</latex>
                     </math>'s occur in columns number <math>
                        <latex>1</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>2</latex>
                     </math>. Therefore, the first and the second column vectors of <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math> form a basis <math>
                        <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                     </math> for the column space of <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math>:</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.array column="3">
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>:=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Set{ (1,1,1,1) , (3,4,2,5) }</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>In particular, <math>
                        <latex>\ColSp{ \Mtrx{A} }</latex>
                     </math> is a sub vector space of <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[4]</latex>
                     </math> of dimension <math>
                        <latex>2</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
		    <answer.showme xmlns="">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>The possible erroneous conclusion is that both <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                     </math> have the same column space. This conclusion is, in general false, as the situation at hand shows:</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>The vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{c}:=(1,1,1,1)</latex>
                     </math> belongs to <math>
                        <latex>\ColSp{ \Mtrx{A} }</latex>
                     </math>. However, <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{c}</latex>
                     </math> cannot belong to the column space of the RREF <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                     </math> of <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>
                     </math>, because every vector in the span of the column vectors of <math>
                        <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex>
                     </math> has the entry ‘<math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math>’ in the 3-rd and 4-th coordinate.</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>Therefore the column spaces of the two matrices are distinct.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
</showme.pack>
